Recently, Heinrich et al. (20) experimentally investigated the force‚Äď velocity curve for tethers extracted from neutrophils by using a biomembrane force probe. Quite surprising, the plateau force exhibited a nonlinear dependence on pulling speed as f Ō≥ Lňô0.25. By contrast, earlier works performed on different and often more limited ranges of pulling velocities had revealed a linear force‚Äď velocity relation, in agreement with the prevalent model (10): f Ō≠ f0 Ō© 2‚ź≤‚ź©effLňô (with ‚ź©eff the effective membrane viscosity). Evans and coworkers (20) resolved this apparent discrepancy by suggesting a shear-thinning model for tether flow. Thus, they demonstrated that all data were consistent. Although attractive, the proposed model remains purely phenomenological and cannot account for a residual force at zero velocity. Here, we wish to show that our physical model, which ignores any presumed viscoelastic effect but simply takes into account the force dependence of the tube radius in the effective viscous drag, is also adequate to fit all previously reported results. The different independent sets of Lňô Ō™ f data (9, 20, 21) used by Evans and coworkers are displayed in log scale in Fig. 3. The solid line is the best fit using Eq. 16. Note that ‚ź©e is the unique floating parameter and that the result depends very weakly on the precise value for f0. First, one may check a posteriori that the explored range of pulling velocities indeed matches with the estimated limits V1 Ō≥ 0.01 ‚źģmÕěs and Lňôc Ō≥ 100 ‚źģmÕěs (Eq. 18) of the permeation regime. Second, it would be important to discuss the significance of the derived surface viscosity ‚ź©e by comparison with previously reported values of effective membrane viscosity ‚ź©eff.
